2. C. Graculus (Shag).

In an expedition on the Stour, Sept. 30, 1820, we perceived a bird at a distance swilnming prodigiously fast. By great exertion we got near it, when it dived and came up two 01· three hundred yards in our rear. The force and velocity of this bird in the water were shown by its leaving behind it a white foam- ing line like the wake of a ship, and which was distinguishable at the distance of several hundred yards.

Genus LXVII. SULA. 1. S. alba (Gannet).

Dr. Hooker informs us that a young Gannet was taken alive some years since in the winter season at Pulhmn, and exhibited at Norwich: it was very fierce. This bird has also been met with both at Lynn and Yarinouth.
